Pydantic-ai generally treats the prompt-templates used to generate the prompts to be sent to the LM as code, for example from the docs

```python

from datetime import date

from pydantic_ai import Agent, RunContext

agent = Agent(
    'openai:gpt-4o',
    deps_type=str,  
    system_prompt="Use the customer's name while replying to them.",  
)


@agent.system_prompt  
def add_the_users_name(ctx: RunContext[str]) -> str:
    return f"The user's name is {ctx.deps}."


@agent.system_prompt
def add_the_date() -> str:  
    return f'The date is {date.today()}.'


result = agent.run_sync('What is the date?', deps='Frank')
print(result.data)
#> Hello Frank, the date today is 2032-01-02.
```

The format strings making up the system prompt would be saved to version control, and treated as code.

[Users have expressed an interest](https://github.com/pydantic/pydantic-ai/issues/913#issuecomment-2655904483) in being able to alter the prompts used by an `Agent` independent of the execution/deployment of the code, as enabled by [GCP's prompt management offering](https://cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/generative-ai/docs/model-reference/prompt-classes) or [Promptly](https://www.trypromptly.com/), much in the way you might want to update the model used by your ML service with a config change as opposed to a code change.

It is possible add this kind of capability on-top of pydantic-ai with the `RunContext`, but I think it would be useful to provide examples or in-library support for connecting to a versioned database (or just a `.json`!) of structured prompts for use with the agents.

```python

from datetime import date
from dataclasses import dataclass
import json

from pydantic_ai import Agent, RunContext

with open("prompt_templates.json") as f:
    PROMPTS = json.load(f)

@dataclass
class MyDeps:  
    prompt_db: dict[str, str]
    user_name: str


agent = Agent(
    'openai:gpt-4o',
    deps_type=MyDeps
)

@agent.system_prompt  
def base_instructions(ctx: RunContext[MyDeps]) -> str:
    return ctx.deps.prompt_db.get("base_instructions")


@agent.system_prompt  
def add_the_users_name(ctx: RunContext[MyDeps]) -> str:
    return ctx.deps.prompt_db.get("name_template").format(ctx.deps.user_name)


@agent.system_prompt
def add_the_date() -> str:  
    return ctx.deps.prompt_db.get("date_template").format(date.today())


result = agent.run_sync('What is the date?', deps=MyDeps(prompt_db=PROMPTS, user_name="Frank"))
print(result.data)
#> Hello Frank, the date today is 2032-01-02.
```

Further down this road is the ability for pydantic-ai to optimize those templates - as implemented in libraries like [dspy](https://github.com/stanfordnlp/dspy) and [adalflow](https://github.com/SylphAI-Inc/AdalFlow), which would be helped if the prompts were in some way parameterized.

